    <p class="section-subtitle">How to stay within VRR range with Quake Live's limited fps values</p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <strong>Two Approaches:</strong><br/>
      <strong>VRR ON (tear-free):</strong> Stay below your monitor's VRR ceiling with an external cap (237-239 for 240 Hz) or use a stable engine step like 200.<br/>
      <strong>VRR OFF (lowest latency):</strong> Many competitive players disable VRR entirely, use <code>com_maxfps 250</code>, and accept tearing for minimum latency.
    </div>

    <div class="info-box" style="background: rgba(46, 204, 113, 0.15); border-color: #2ecc71;">
      <strong>VRR Latency Note:</strong> The latency concerns with VRR are minimal when your monitor's refresh rate is significantly higher than your FPS cap. For example, a 360Hz monitor with <code>com_maxfps 250</code> means VRR is essentially "free" ‚Äî you get tear-free visuals with negligible latency penalty because there's so much headroom above your cap.
    </div>

    <div class="hz-cards">
